projects.description:
Upgrade of the World Press Photo travelling exhibition display support system, originally designed by Benno Premsela.
Project team: Femke van der Valk, Erik de Kruijff, Kari Lundelin;
Consultants: Corine Dijst, Arthur Herrman, Jeroen Kummer, Bas Vroege;
Design by Heijdens Karwei.

profile_positions.description:
Responsible for realizing 25 international travelling photo exhibitions annually. Worked closely together with local partner, including contract negotiations and logistic planning. Traveled to venues to supervise installation team. Conducted a press conference and interviews for print media, radio, and television. Gave a speech at the opening reception and liaised with sponsors, local photography community and local dignitaries. Conducted evaluation with the partner.

List of partner venues include:
UK: Royal Festival Hall (London), Scottish Parliament (Edinburgh);
France: Carrousel du Louvre (Paris), La Filature (Mulhouse), Espace Malraux (Chambéry);
Germany: Gruner+Jahr Pressehaus (Hamburg), Kulturort Depot (Dortmund);
Italy: Museo di Roma in Trastevere (Rome), Galleria Carla Sozzani (Milan);
Spain: Biblioteca Nacional (Madrid), Circulo de Bellas Artes (Madrid);
Portugal: Museu da Electricidade (Lisbon), Forum da Maia (Porto);
Austria: Galerie Westlicht (Vienna);
Scandinavia: National Museum of Denmark (Copenhagen), Galleri Kontrast (Stockholm);
Poland: Galleria Zacheta (Warsaw), Bunkier Sztuki (Krakow), Centrum Sztuki Wspolczesnei (Torun);
US: Museum of Tolerance (Los Angeles);
China: National Museum of China (Beijing);
South Africa: Standard Bank Gallery (Johannesburg), Castle of Good Hope (Cape Town);
Brazil: Museu de Arte Contemporaneo (Rio de Janeiro);
Egypt: Cairo Opera Gallery (Cairo).

In addition to galleries and museums, set up exhibitions and events in other public spaces, such as city halls, main railway stations (in cooperation with Die Bahn in Germany) and shopping centres and department store galleries (such as an annual tour of Japan in cooperation with Asahi Shimbun and Tokyu Department Stores) and at the Winter Garden of the World Financial Center in New York City.
